<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="60" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1063,1905]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,221,1063,1089]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Male.</emphasis>
Forewing length 2.1 mm. Coloration of the body (in alcohol) dark grayish brown. Abdominal sternum VII with a spine. Segment VIII annular, becoming narrower towards the venter, where it is reduced to a thin medial strip (
<figureCitation box="[312,387,1141,1167]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 12" captionStartId="2.[151,269,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[232,1362,207,1866]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[221,1372,197,1887]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 12. Figs. 1 – 8, Alisotrichia cainguas, n. sp.: 1: Head, dorsal view. 2: Maxillary palp. Figs. 3 – 5, abdominal segment VIII: 3: ventral. 4: lateral. 5: abdominal segments VIII – X, dorsal. Figs. 6 – 7: abdominal segment IX: 6: lateral. 7: ventral. 8: phallus. Figs. 9 – 12, Metrichia pitu, n. sp., male genitalia: 9: lateral. 10: ventral. 11: dorsal. 12: phallus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189022/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
Fig. 
<number box="[369,387,1141,1167]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
). Sternum IX lengthened, produced, and lightly truncated anteriorly. Tergum IX short, rounded posteriorly, with a lobe that situates above the phallus; apex deeply cleft mesally (the cleft is narrow posteriorly and rounded at the base) (
<figureCitation box="[590,718,1218,1244]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 12" captionStartId="2.[151,269,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[232,1362,207,1866]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[221,1372,197,1887]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 12. Figs. 1 – 8, Alisotrichia cainguas, n. sp.: 1: Head, dorsal view. 2: Maxillary palp. Figs. 3 – 5, abdominal segment VIII: 3: ventral. 4: lateral. 5: abdominal segments VIII – X, dorsal. Figs. 6 – 7: abdominal segment IX: 6: lateral. 7: ventral. 8: phallus. Figs. 9 – 12, Metrichia pitu, n. sp., male genitalia: 9: lateral. 10: ventral. 11: dorsal. 12: phallus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189022/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
Figs. 
<number box="[656,718,1218,1244]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" value="10.0" valueMax="11.0" valueMin="9.0">9–11</number>
</figureCitation>
). Lateral appendages quadrangular, with the apex concave in lateral view. Cerci short and rounded. Dorsal appendages resembling curved, long spines, shorter than the dorsal lobe of segment IX. Phallus long, reaching segment II; with a pair of robust, strongly pigmented, apical spines; central tubule dark up to half its length (
<figureCitation box="[710,798,1334,1360]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 12" captionStartId="2.[151,269,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[232,1362,207,1866]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[221,1372,197,1887]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 12. Figs. 1 – 8, Alisotrichia cainguas, n. sp.: 1: Head, dorsal view. 2: Maxillary palp. Figs. 3 – 5, abdominal segment VIII: 3: ventral. 4: lateral. 5: abdominal segments VIII – X, dorsal. Figs. 6 – 7: abdominal segment IX: 6: lateral. 7: ventral. 8: phallus. Figs. 9 – 12, Metrichia pitu, n. sp., male genitalia: 9: lateral. 10: ventral. 11: dorsal. 12: phallus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189022/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
Fig. 
<number box="[765,798,1334,1360]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="60" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1063,1905]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,325,1373,1399]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Based on the structure of the male genitalia this species seems to be more closely related to a group of species from Central 
<collectingCountry box="[521,627,1412,1438]" name="United States of America" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">America</collectingCountry>
, than with the species known regionally, especially with 
<taxonomicName authority="Flint 1968" authorityName="Flint" authorityYear="1968" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Metrichia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="similis">
<emphasis box="[1317,1435,1412,1437]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">M. similis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Flint" box="[159,285,1450,1476]" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" refString="Flint, O. S., Jr. (1968) Bredin - Archbold - Smithsonian Biological Survey of Dominica. 9. The Trichoptera (caddisflies) of the Lesser Antilles. Proceedings of the United States National Museum, 125, 1 - 86." type="journal article" year="1968">
Flint 
<number box="[225,285,1450,1476]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" value="1968.0">1968</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[367,487,1450,1476]" name="Dominica" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Dominica</collectingCountry>
, whose males are characterized by having the segment X sclerotized and with a V-shaped cleft at the apex (absent in other known species of the genus); segment IX oval anteriorly, and lateral appendages, that are longer than the dorsal lobe, with a deep V-shaped cleft at the apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1063,1905]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
This is the 
<number box="[337,352,1569,1595]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" value="2.0">2</number>
nd species of 
<taxonomicName box="[512,634,1569,1594]" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Metrichia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[512,634,1569,1594]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Metrichia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
described from Salto Encantado Provincial Park. Previously 
<taxonomicName authority="Angrisano 2005" authorityName="Angrisano" authorityYear="2005" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Metrichia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuniapiru">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">M. cuniapiru</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Angrisano" box="[276,468,1608,1634]" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" refString="Angrisano, E. B. &amp; Sganga, J. V. (2005) Contribution to the knowledge of Metrichia Ross from Argentina (Trichoptera: Hydroptilidae: Ochrotrichiini). Aquatic Insects, 27, 113 - 123." type="journal article" year="2005">
Angrisano 
<number box="[408,468,1608,1634]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" value="2005.0">2005</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(in 
<bibRefCitation author="Angrisano" box="[518,841,1608,1634]" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" refString="Angrisano, E. B. &amp; Sganga, J. V. (2005) Contribution to the knowledge of Metrichia Ross from Argentina (Trichoptera: Hydroptilidae: Ochrotrichiini). Aquatic Insects, 27, 113 - 123." type="journal article" year="2005">
Angrisano &amp; Sganga 
<number box="[779,841,1608,1634]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" value="2005.0">2005</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) was described. The latter differentiates from the new one by: tergum X membranous, lateral appendages wide, short, and relatively truncated at the apex, segment IX oval anteriorly, phallus without dark, conspicuous spines at the apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
